  "history_of_nyc_prospect_park": "Prospect Park in New York City has a rich historical background. It was originally a farm belonging to a New Netherland farmer. Later, the country of England gave the park to Trinity Church, which built St. John's Chapel and some townhouses around the park. By 1827, the residents of the area were very wealthy. In the 1850s, many of these wealthy individuals moved out. In 1866, Cornelius Vanderbilt purchased the park for a railroad terminal. This terminal was later destroyed in 1927. The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey's Holland Tunnel was constructed in 1927, which is located at the Manhattan end of the Holland Tunnel to New Jersey."
